ez","meanings":["Hispanic: altered form of Spanish <b>Ramírez</b> (see   Ramirez  )."]},{"name":"Rameriz","meanings":["(1997: 180;2007: 712; 2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Luis, Alejandro, Felipe, Fermin, Lupe, Manuel, Margarita, Margarito, Miguel, Pedro.","Hispanic: altered form of Spanish <b>Ramírez</b> (see   Ramirez  )."]},{"name":"Ramiro","meanings":["Portuguese, Galician, and Spanish: from the personal name <i>Ramiro</i>, of Visigothic origin, presumably composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>māri</i>, <i>mēri</i> ‘fame, famous’."]}]},{"name":"DIAZ","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Carlos, Luis, Manuel, Jesus, Francisco, Jorge, Rafael, Miguel, Pedro, Roberto.","Spanish (<b>Díaz</b>): patronymic from the medieval personal name <i>Didacus</i> (see   Diego  ).","Jewish (Sephardic): adoption of the Spanish surname (see 1 above) at the moment of conversion to Roman Catholicism. After the return to Judaism (generations later), some descendants retained the name their families used as Catholics."],"variants":[{"name":"Diazdeleon","meanings":["Spanish: combination of the surname <b>Díaz</b> (see   Diaz  ) and the name León (see   Leon  ) with the preposition <i>de</i> ‘of’."]},{"name":"Diego","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Francisco, Juan, Fernando, Jose, Miguel, Mario, Maximo, Salvador, Aida, Ana, Domingo.","Spanish: from the very common male personal name <i>Diego</i>, which in the Spanish-speaking world is usually taken to be a shortened form of   Santiago  . However, this may be only a folk etymology. The personal name is found in the Middle Ages in the Latin forms <i>Didacus</i> and <i>Didagus</i>, probably a derivative of Greek <i>didachē</i> ‘doctrine, teaching’. However, in view of the fact that this personal name is unknown outside the Iberian Peninsula, it may actually have a pre-Roman origin."]},{"name":"Diez","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Jorge, Juan, Fernando, Pedro, Rafael, Roberto, Angel, Eduardo, Mario, Ricardo.","Spanish (<b>Díez</b>): variant of <b>Díaz</b> (see   Diaz  ).","German: variant of   Dietz  ."]}]},{"name":"Diego","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Origin uncertain; perhaps from   Santiago   or from a native Iberian name found in Latin as <i>Didacus</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1354684,"age":39,"year":"1200","julianDay":2159351,"description":"The Christian territory controlled the Kingdoms of Aragon, Navarre, and Castile.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Diego RAMIREZ DIAZ was born in 1161, in Vascongadas, Spain, his father, Iñigo RAMIREZ IÑIGUEZ, was 30 and his mother, Toda Díaz de Haro, was 28. He married Urraca Perez de Bureba Iñiguez López about 1179, in Spain. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1230, at the age of 69, and was buried in Burgos, Castilla y León, Spain."},"et":{"1161–1230":"1161–1230","1159–1230":"1159–1230","1173–1239":"1173–1239","1182–Male":"1182–Surnud","1131–1215":"1131–1215","1133–1216":"1133–1216","1230":"1230","1131":"1131","1173":"1173","1161":"1161","1160":"1160","1182":"1182","1239":"1239","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1159":"1159","Abt 1179":"umbes 1179","1200":"1200","1133":"1133","16 January 1216":"16. jaanuar 1216","Abt 1182":"umbes 1182","Zúñiga, Zúñiga, Navarra, España":"Zúñiga, Zuñiga, Nafarroa, Hispaania","Vascongadas, España":"Vascongadas, Hispaania","Burgos, Castilla y León, España":"Burgos, Castilla y León, Hispaania","Of,,, Spain":"Hispaania",",,, Spain":"Hispaania","LEYVA, NAVARRA, ESPAÑA":"Hispaania"},"fi":{"1161–1230":"1161–1230","1159–1230":"1159–1230","1173–1239":"1173–1239","1182–Male":"1182–Kuollut","1131–1215":"1131–1215","1133–1216":"1133–1216","1230":"1230","1131":"11